defensive-suite — fapolicyd block-hash rules (M4 prevention baseline)

  >>> SHIPPED, NOT APPLIED. REVIEW FIRST. VALIDATE IN A VM. <<<
  The build/tests never write a fapolicyd rule. agentd's block-hash response
  actuator (M3) and this baseline both go through fapolicyd; nothing here is
  applied automatically.

WHAT FAPOLICYD GIVES US
-----------------------
fapolicyd is an application allow/deny daemon. It can DENY execution of a binary
by SHA-256 hash or by path. The defensive-suite uses it two ways:

  1. M3 response actuator `block-hash`: agentd writes a deny-by-SHA-256 rule when
     an operator chooses to block a flagged binary. It is REVERSIBLE — remove the
     rule file and reload. agentd dry-runs the rule first and refuses to deny a
     critical system binary.

  2. M4 prevention baseline (this dir): a small, reviewed set of static deny
     rules you maintain by hand for known-bad hashes.

THE rules.d PATH (where deny rules live)
----------------------------------------
On a standard install, fapolicyd reads rule files from:

    /etc/fapolicyd/rules.d/        # *.rules, lexically ordered (e.g. 50-dsuite.rules)
    /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.trust # the trust database (known-good files)

A deny-by-hash rule looks like (REVIEW; do not blind-copy):

    # 50-dsuite.rules — deny a specific known-bad binary by SHA-256
    deny perm=execute exe=/ : sha256hash=<64-hex-of-the-bad-binary>

A deny-by-path rule:

    deny perm=execute exe=/ : path=/tmp/suspicious-dropper

After EDITING a rule file you must compile + reload (privileged — REVIEW):

    sudo fapolicyd-cli --update        # recompile rules.d into the running policy
    # or, if your build expects a service reload:
    sudo systemctl reload fapolicyd

ARMING DISCIPLINE
-----------------
  - Run `agentd preflight` first — it reports whether fapolicyd is present AND
    active. block-hash and these rules do nothing if the daemon is inactive.
  - fapolicyd starts in PERMISSIVE on many distros; confirm enforce mode only
    after you've trusted your real binaries, or you will block your own desktop.
    Check /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.conf (permissive = 1 → 0) — VM-FIRST.
  - NEVER deny a critical system binary (shell, coreutils, the package manager,
    sshd). agentd's block-hash guardrails refuse these; a hand-written rule has
    no such guard, so review every hash.

ROLLBACK
--------
    sudo rm /etc/fapolicyd/rules.d/50-dsuite.rules
    sudo fapolicyd-cli --update        # (or systemctl reload fapolicyd)

Reference: see deploy/RESPONSE.md for how the M3 block-hash actuator uses the
same path, and deploy/ENFORCE.md for the overall arming runbook.
